# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: allan-octavian-hume
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] His father died while he was young, as in 1851 Sinnett was listed as a "Scholar – London University", living with his mother Jane Sinnett, an author and translator, who is listed as a widow and whose occupation is listed as "Periodical Literature"; his older sister Sophia, age 22, was a teacher.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] Jane's sister Sarah, age 48, was also a teacher.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] In 1870 Sinnett married his wife Patience, probably in the London area.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] He is listed in the 1871 England Census at age 31, as a Journalist, born in Middlesex.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] His wife Patience is 27, and her mother Clarissa Edenson a "Landowner", is living with them.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] In 1880 Helena Blavatsky and Henry Steel Olcott visited the Sinnetts at their summer home in Simla.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] The *Mahatma Letters*, which generated the controversy that later helped lead to the split of the Theosophical Society were mostly written to Sinnett or his wife Patience.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] The letters started at this time when Sinnett asked Blavatsky whether if he wrote a letter to her Mahatmas, she could arrange to have it delivered.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] By 1884 Sinnett was back in England, where that year Constance Wachtmeister states that she met Blavatsky at the home of the Sinnetts in London.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] Sinnett asked Charles Webster Leadbeater to come back to England to tutor his son Percy and George Arundale.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] Leadbeater agreed and brought with him one of his pupils Curuppumullage Jinarajadasa.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] Using "astral clairvoyance" Leadbeater assisted William Scott-Elliot to write his book *The Story of Atlantis*, for which Sinnett wrote the preface.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] Sinnett was later president of the London Lodge of the Society.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-p-sinnett] His son Percy is also listed as an author and born in India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] He became a vegetarian as a young man through reading the work of T.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] Bailey Walker and joined the Vegetarian Society in 1877.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] He worked as an analytical chemist in Manchester and for James Woolley, Sons and Co., manufacture chemists.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] Duncan had studied with Carl Remigius Fresenius.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] He was also a Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] In 1884, Duncan authored a pamphlet *The Chemistry of Foods*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] It was republished as *The Chemistry of Food and Nutrition* by the Vegetarian Society in 1905.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] Forward noted that Duncan had given "valuable aid to the Vegetarian Society in connection with the chemistry of food, and has contributed many useful essays and papers on the subject".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] Duncan was on the executive committee of the Vegetarian Society in 1880 and later served as a vice-president.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] In 1899, Duncan commented that "a grain of wheat contains everything that is required for nutrition and these constituents are in the right proportion, so that were it necessary we could live on wheatmeal bread and water alone".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] He later moved to New South Wales, Australia but remained in contact with vegetarians in England and was an officer for the Vegetarian Society in 1935.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] He married Annie Margaret Allison in 1890.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] They had two children: Frank and Phyllis.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] Duncan died in Punchbowl, New South Wales in 1946, aged 90.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/a-w-duncan] He was privately cremated at Rockwood crematorium.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The **shikra** (***Tachyspiza badia***) is a small bird of prey in the family Accipitridae found widely distributed in Asia and Africa where it is also called the **little banded goshawk**.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The African forms may represent a separate species but have usually been considered as subspecies of the shikra.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The shikra is very similar in appearance, as well as behavior, at least to some degree, to other species including the Chinese sparrowhawk (*Tachyspiza soloensis*, formerly *Accipiter soloensis*), Eurasian goshawk (*Astur gentilis*) and Eurasian sparrowhawk (*Accipiter nisus*).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] They have a sharp two-note call and exhibit the flap-and-glide flight style typical of *Tachyspiza* and *Accipiter* hawks.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Their calls are imitated by drongos and the common hawk-cuckoo resembles it in plumage.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] This species was formerly placed in the genus *Accipiter*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The shikra was formally described in 1788/1789 by the German naturalist Johann Friedrich Gmelin in his revised and expanded edition of Carl Linnaeus's *Systema Naturae*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] He placed it with the eagles, hawks and their relatives in the genus *Falco* and coined the binomial name *Falco badius*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Gmelin's description was based on the "brown hawk" from Ceylon that had been described and illustrated in 1776 by the English naturalist Peter Brown.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The shikra was formerly placed in the large and diverse genus *Accipiter*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] In 2024 a comprehensive molecular phylogenetic study of the Accipitridae confirmed earlier work that had shown that the genus was polyphyletic.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] To resolve the non-monophyly, *Accipiter* was divided into six genera.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The genus *Tachyspiza* was resurrected to accommodate the shikra together with 26 other species that had previously been placed in *Accipiter*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The resurrected genus had been introduced in 1844 by the German naturalist Johann Jakob Kaup.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The word *Tachyspiza* combines the Ancient Greek ταχυς (*takhus*) meaning "fast" with σπιζιας (*spizias*) meaning "hawk".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The specific epithet *badia* is Latin meaning "chestnut-coloured" or "brown".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The shikra is a small raptor (26–30 cm (10–12 in) long) and, like most other *Tachyspiza* hawks, has short rounded wings and a narrow and somewhat long tail.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Adults are whitish on the underside with fine rufous bars while the upperparts are grey.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The lower belly is less barred and the thighs are whitish.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Males have a red iris while the females have a less red (yellowish orange) iris and brownish upperparts apart from heavier barring on the underparts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The mesial stripe on the throat is dark but narrow.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] In flight the male seen from below shows a light wing lining (underwing coverts) and has blackish wing tips.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] When seen from above the tail bands are faintly marked on the lateral tail feathers and not as strongly marked as in the Eurasian sparrowhawk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The central tail feathers are unbanded and only have a dark terminal band.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Juveniles have dark streaks and spots on the upper breast and the wing is narrowly barred while the tail has dark but narrow bands.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] A post juvenile transitional plumage is found with very strong barring on the contour feathers of the underside.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The call is *pee-wee*, the first note being higher and the second being longer.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] In flight the calls are shorter and sharper *kik-ki ... kik-ki*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The Chinese sparrowhawk is somewhat similar in appearance but has swollen bright orange ceres and yellow legs with the wing tips entirely black.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Subspecies *cenchroides* is larger and paler and found in Turkestan, Afghanistan and eastern Iran.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The Indian population *dussumieri* is resident on the plains and lower hills (up to 1,400 m (4,590 ft) in the Himalayas).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The nominate form is found in Sri Lanka and has somewhat darker grey upperparts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The Burmese shikra *A. b. poliopsis* may represent a distinct species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The population on the island of Car Nicobar, earlier treated as a subspecies *butleri* and that on Katchal Island, *obsoletus* are now treated as a sub-species within a full species, the Nicobar sparrowhawk (*Tachyspiza butleri*).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The west African population *T. b. sphenurus* is migratory while the southern African *T. b. polyzonoides* is more nomadic in its movements.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] In Asia only *T. b. cenchroides* is migratory.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The shikra is found in a range of habitats including forests, farmland and urban areas.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] They are usually seen singly or in pairs.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The flight is typical with flaps and glides.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] During the breeding season pairs will soar on thermals and stoop at each other.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Their flight usually draws alarms among smaller birds and squirrels.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] They feed on rodents (including *Meriones hurrianae*), squirrels, small birds, small reptiles (mainly lizards but sometimes small snakes) and insects.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Small birds usually dive through foliage to avoid a shikra and a Small Blue Kingfisher has been observed diving into water to escape.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Babblers have been observed to rally together to drive away a shikra.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] They will descend to the ground to feast on emerging winged termites, hunt at dusk for small bats (such as *Cynopterus sphinx*) and in rare instances they may even resort to feed on carrion.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] In one instance a male was found feeding on a dead chick at the nest.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Their calls are mimicked by drongos and this behaviour is thought to aid in stealing food by alarming other birds that the drongos associate with.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The breeding season in India is in summer from March to June.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The nest is a platform similar to that of crows lined with grass.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Both sexes help build the nest, twigs being carried in their feet.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Like crows, they may also make use of metal wires.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The usual clutch is 3 to 4 eggs (when eggs are removed they lay replacements and one observer noted that they could lay as many as 7 in a season) which are pale bluish grey stippled on the broad end in black.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The shikra was a favourite among falconers in India and Pakistan due to the ease with which it could be trained and was frequently used to procure food for the more prized falcons.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] They were noted for their pluck and ability to take much larger birds including partridges, crows and even young peafowl.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The word *shikra* or *shikara* means hunter in the Hindi language (the male was called *chipak* or *chipka* based on call) The word Shikra is borrowed from the Urdu word (شِـكْـره) which is derived from the word shikari (شِكارى) meaning hunter.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] The word is also used in the French name *Le Chicquera* which was however given to the red-necked falcon by Levaillant in 1799.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-badius] Famous Punjabi poet Shiv Kumar Batalvi wrote a poem called "Main Ik Shikra Yaar Banaya" about a lost love wherein he compares her to a shikra.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The **Eurasian sparrowhawk** (***Accipiter nisus***), also known as the **northern sparrowhawk** or simply the **sparrowhawk**, is a small bird of prey in the family Accipitridae.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Adult male Eurasian sparrowhawks have bluish grey upperparts and orange-barred underparts; females and juveniles are brown above with brown barring below.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The female is up to 25% larger than the male – one of the greatest size differences between the sexes in any bird species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Though it is a predator which specialises in catching woodland birds, the Eurasian sparrowhawk can be found in any habitat and often hunts garden birds in towns and cities.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Males tend to take smaller birds, including tits, finches and sparrows; females catch primarily thrushes and starlings but are capable of killing birds weighing 500 g (18 oz) or more.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk is found throughout the temperate and subtropical parts of the Old World; whilst birds from the northern parts of the range migrate south for winter, their southern counterparts remain resident or make dispersive movements.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks breed in suitable woodland of any type, with the nest, measuring up to 60 cm (24 in) across, built using twigs in a tree.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Four or five pale blue, brown-spotted eggs are laid; the success of the breeding attempt is dependent on the female maintaining a high weight while the male brings her food.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The chicks hatch after 33 days and fledge after 24 to 28 days.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The probability of a juvenile surviving its first year is 34%, with 69% of adults surviving from one year to the next.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Mortality in young males is greater than that of young females and the typical lifespan is four years.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] This species is now one of the most common birds of prey in Europe, although the population crashed after the Second World War.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Organochlorine insecticides used to treat seeds before sowing built up in the bird population, and the concentrations in Eurasian sparrowhawks were enough to kill some outright and incapacitate others; affected birds laid eggs with fragile shells, which broke during incubation.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] However, its population recovered after the chemicals were banned, and it is now relatively common, classified as being of least concern by BirdLife International.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk's hunting behaviour has brought it into conflict with humans for hundreds of years, particularly racing pigeon owners and people rearing poultry and gamebirds.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It has also been blamed for decreases in passerine populations.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Studies of racing-pigeon deaths found that Eurasian sparrowhawks were responsible for less than 1%.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Falconers have utilised the Eurasian sparrowhawk since at least the 16th century; although the species has a reputation for being difficult to train, it is also praised for its courage.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The species features in Teutonic mythology and is mentioned in works by writers including William Shakespeare, Alfred, Lord Tennyson and Ted Hughes.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Within the family Accipitridae, the Eurasian sparrowhawk is a member of the large genus *Accipiter*, which consists of small to medium-sized woodland hawks.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Most of the Old World members of the genus are called sparrowhawks or goshawks.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The species' name dates back to the Middle English word *sperhauk* and Old English *spearhafoc*, a hawk which hunts sparrows.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Old Norse name for the Eurasian sparrowhawk, *sparrhaukr*, was thought to have been coined by Vikings who encountered falconry in England.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] English folk names for the Eurasian sparrowhawk include *blue hawk*, referring to the adult male's colouration, as well as *hedge hawk*, *spar hawk*, *spur hawk* and *stone falcon*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk was described by Carl Linnaeus in his 1758 landmark 10th edition of *Systema Naturae* as *Falco nisus*, but moved to its present genus by French zoologist Mathurin Jacques Brisson in 1760.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The current scientific name is derived from the Latin *accipiter*, meaning 'hawk', and *nisus*, the sparrowhawk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] According to Greek mythology Nisus, the king of Megara, was turned into a sparrowhawk after his daughter, Scylla, cut off his purple lock of hair to present to her lover (and Nisus' enemy), Minos.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk forms a superspecies with the rufous-chested sparrowhawk of eastern and southern Africa, and possibly the Madagascar sparrowhawk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Geographic variation is clinal, with birds becoming larger and paler in the eastern part of the range compared to the western part.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk is a small bird of prey with short, broad wings and a long tail, both adaptations to manoeuvring through trees.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Females can be up to 25% larger than males and weigh up to twice as much.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Marked size difference in this direction is unusual in higher vertebrates but typical in birds of prey, and most marked in birds of prey which hunt other birds.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] He has slate-grey upperparts (sometimes tending to bluish), with finely red-barred underparts, which can look plain orange from a distance; his irides are orange-yellow or orange-red.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] She has dark brown or greyish-brown upperparts, brown-barred underparts and bright yellow to orange irides.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The juvenile is warm brown above, with rusty fringes to the upperparts, and coarsely barred or spotted brown below, with pale yellow eyes; its throat has dark streaks and lacks a mesial (midline) stripe.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk's pale underparts and darker upperparts are an example of countershading, which helps to break up the bird's outline.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Countershading is exhibited by birds of prey that hunt birds and other fast-moving animals.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The horizontal barring seen on adult Eurasian sparrowhawks is typical of woodland-dwelling predatory birds and the adult male's bluish colour is also seen in other bird-eating raptors, including the peregrine falcon, the merlin and other *Accipiters*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A study using stuffed bird models found that small birds are less likely to approach common cuckoos (a brood parasite), which have barred underparts like the Eurasian sparrowhawk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian reed warblers were found to be more aggressive to cuckoos which looked less hawk-like, meaning that the resemblance to the hawk (mimicry) helps the cuckoo to access the nests of potential hosts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk's small bill is used for plucking feathers and pulling prey apart rather than killing or cutting.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Its long legs and toes are an adaptation for catching and eating birds.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The outer toe is fairly long and slender; the inner toe and back toe are relatively short and thick.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The middle toe is very long and can be used to grasp objects, and a protuberance on the underside of the toe means that the digit can be closed without leaving a gap, which helps with gripping.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The flight is a characteristic flap-flap-glide, with the glide creating an undulating pattern.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] This species is similar in size to the Levant sparrowhawk, but larger than the shikra (the calls are however different); the male is only slightly larger than the merlin.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Because of the overlap in sizes, the female can be confused with the similarly sized male Eurasian Goshawk, but lacks the bulk of that species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks are smaller, more slender and have shorter wings, a square-ended tail and fly with faster wingbeats.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A confusion species in China is the besra, although *A. n. melaschistos* is considerably larger.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In Great Britain, Eurasian sparrowhawks living further north are bigger than their more southerly counterparts, with wing length (the most reliable indicator of body size) increasing by an average of 0.86 mm (0.034 in) in males, and 0.75 mm (0.030 in) in females, for each degree further north.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A widespread species throughout the temperate and subtropical parts of the Old World, the Eurasian sparrowhawk is resident or breeds in an estimated global range of 23,600,000 km2 (9,100,000 sq mi) and had an estimated population of 1.5 million birds in 2009.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Although global population trends have not been analysed, numbers seem to be stable, so it has been classified as being of least concern by IUCN.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The race *granti*, with 100 pairs resident on Madeira and 200 pairs on the Canary Islands, is threatened by loss of habitat, egg-collecting and illegal hunting, and is listed on Annex I of the European Commission Birds Directive.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It is one of the most common birds of prey in Europe, along with the common kestrel and common buzzard.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Norwegian and Albanian populations are declining and, in many parts of Europe, Eurasian sparrowhawks are still shot.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] However, this low-level persecution has not affected the populations badly.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In the UK, the population increased by 108% between 1970 and 2005, but saw a 1% decline over 1994–2006.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In Ireland it is the most common bird of prey, breeding even near the city centre of Dublin, where it frequents parks and large gardens.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] This species is prevalent in most woodland types in its range, and also in more open country with scattered trees.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks prefer to hunt the edges of wooded areas, but migrant birds can be seen in any habitat.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The increased proportion of medium-aged stands of trees created by modern forestry techniques have benefited *Accipiter nisus*, according to a Norwegian study.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Unlike its larger relative the Eurasian Goshawk, it can be seen in gardens and in urban areas and will even breed in city parks if they have a certain density of tall trees.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks from colder regions of northern Europe and Asia migrate south for the winter, some to north Africa (some as far as equatorial east Africa) and India; members of the southern populations are resident or disperse.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Juveniles begin their migration earlier than adults and juvenile females move before juvenile males.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A study of Eurasian sparrowhawks in southern Scotland found that ringed birds which had been raised on "high grade" territories were recovered in greater proportion than birds which came from "low grade" territories.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] This suggested that the high grade territories produced young which survived better.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The recovery rate also declined with increased elevation of the ground.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] After the post-fledging period, female birds dispersed greater distances than did males.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk is a major predator of smaller woodland birds, though only 10% of its hunting attacks are successful.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It hunts by surprise attack, using hedges, tree-belts, copses, orchards and other cover near woodland areas; its choice of habitat is dictated by these requirements.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It also makes use of gardens in built-up areas, taking advantage of the prey found there.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It waits, hidden, for birds to come near, then breaks cover and flies out fast and low.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A chase may follow, with the hawk even flipping upside-down to grab the victim from below or following it on foot through vegetation.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It can "stoop" onto prey from a great height.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Male Eurasian sparrowhawks regularly kill birds weighing up to 40 g (1.4 oz) and sometimes up to 120 g (4.2 oz) or more; females can tackle prey up to 500 g (18 oz) or more.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A recent study found that on average, female sparrowhawk prey were two and a half times heavier than that of the male.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The weight of food consumed by adult birds daily is estimated to be 40–50 g (1.4–1.8 oz) for males and 50–70 g (1.8–2.5 oz) for females.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] During one year, a pair of Eurasian sparrowhawks could take 2,200 house sparrows, 600 common blackbirds or 110 wood pigeons.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Species that feed in the open, far from cover, or are conspicuous by their behaviour or coloration, are taken more often by Eurasian sparrowhawks.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] For example, great tits and house sparrows are vulnerable to attack.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks may account for more than 50% of deaths in certain species, but the extent varies from area to area.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Males tend to take tits, finches, sparrows and buntings; females often take thrushes and starlings.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] More than 120 bird species have been recorded as prey and individual Eurasian sparrowhawks may specialise in certain prey.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The birds taken are usually adults or fledglings, though chicks in the nest and carrion are sometimes eaten.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Small mammals, including mice, bats, voles, squirrels, shrews, and young rabbits, are sometimes caught but insects are eaten only very rarely.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Small birds are killed on impact or when squeezed by the Eurasian sparrowhawk's foot, especially the two long claws.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Larger quarry (such as doves and magpies) may not die immediately but succumb during feather plucking and eating.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Victims which struggle are "kneaded" by the hawk, using its talons to squeeze and stab.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] When dealing with large prey species which peck and flap, the hawk's long legs help in restraining the prey.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It stands on top of its prey to pluck and pull it apart.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The feathers are plucked and usually the breast muscles are eaten first.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The bones are left, but can be broken using the notch in the bill.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Like other birds of prey, Eurasian sparrowhawks produce pellets containing indigestible parts of their prey.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] These range from 25 to 35 mm (0.98 to 1.38 in) long and 10–18 mm (0.39–0.71 in) wide and are round at one end and more narrow and pointed at the other.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] They are usually composed of small feathers, as the larger ones are plucked and not consumed.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] During hunting, this species can fly 2–3 km (1.2–1.9 mi) per day.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It rises above tree level mostly to display, soar above territory and to make longer journeys.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A study looked at the effect on the population of blue tits in an area where a pair of Eurasian sparrowhawks began to breed in 1990.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It found that the annual adult survival rate for the tits in that area dropped from 0.485 to 0.376 (the rate in adjacent plots did not change).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The size of the breeding population was not changed, but there were fewer non-breeding blue tits in the population.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In Sussex, the impact of Eurasian sparrowhawk predation on grey partridges was highest when the partridge density was lowest.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A 10-year study in Scotland showed that Eurasian sparrowhawks did not select the common redshanks they predated according to the waders' size or condition, probably because of the hawks' surprise-attack hunting technique.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In Britain, the increase in population of the Eurasian sparrowhawk coincides with the decline of the house sparrow population.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Another study found that the risk of predation for a bird targeted by a Eurasian sparrowhawk or Eurasian Goshawk increased 25-fold if the prey was infected with the blood parasite *Leucocytozoon*, and birds with avian malaria were 16 times more likely to be killed.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Natural predators of the Eurasian sparrowhawk include the barn owl, the tawny owl, the Eurasian Goshawk, the peregrine falcon, the golden eagle, the bald eagle, the eagle owl, the red fox, the stone marten and the pine marten.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The eggs are pale blue with brown spots and each measure 35–46 mm (1.4–1.8 in) x 28–35 mm (1.1–1.4 in), and weigh about 22.5 g (0.79 oz) of which 8% is shell in a healthy egg.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Usually a clutch of four or five eggs is laid.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The eggs are generally laid in the morning with an interval of 2–3 days between each egg.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] If a clutch is lost, up to two further eggs may be laid that are smaller than the earlier eggs.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The altricial, downy chicks hatch after 33 days of incubation.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] After hatching, the female cares for and feeds the chicks for the first 8–14 days of life, and also during bad weather after that.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The male provides food, up to six kills per day in the first week increasing to eight per day in the third and 10 per day in the last week in the nest, by which time the female is also hunting.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] By 24–28 days after hatching, the young birds start to perch on branches near the nest and take their first flight.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] They are fed by their parents for a further 28–30 days, staying close to the nest while growing and practicing flying.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] At this stage they are extremely vocal, and their cries to their parents can often be heard a considerable distance away.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The young hawks disperse after their parents stop provisioning them.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Though they receive the same amount of food, male chicks (roughly half the size of females) mature more quickly and seem to be ready to leave the nest sooner.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In a study in the Forest of Ae, south-west Scotland, it was found that 21% of nestlings over two days old died, with the causes of death being starvation, wet weather, predation and desertion by the parents.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The parasite *Leucocytozoon toddi* can be passed from parent to nestling at the nest, possibly because of the number of birds sharing a small space, thus allowing transmission.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk breeds in well-grown, extensive areas of woodland, often coniferous or mixed, preferring forest with a structure neither too dense nor too open, to allow a choice of flight paths.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The nest can be located in the fork of a tree, often near the trunk and where two or three branches begin, on a horizontal branch in the lower canopy, or near the top of a tall shrub.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A new nest is built every year, generally close to the nest of the previous year, and sometimes using an old wood pigeon (*A. n. melaschistos* frequently uses the old nests of jungle crows) nest as a base; the male does most of the work.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The structure, made of loose twigs up to 60 cm (2.0 ft) long, has an average diameter of 60 cm (24 in).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] When the eggs are laid, a lining of fine twigs or bark chippings is added.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] During the breeding season, the adult male Eurasian sparrowhawk loses a small amount of weight while feeding his mate before she lays eggs, and also when the young are large and require more food.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The weight of the adult female is highest in May, when laying eggs, and lowest in August after the breeding cycle is complete.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A study suggested that the number of eggs and subsequent breeding success are dependent on the female maintaining a high weight while the male is feeding her.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Sexual maturity is reached at between 1–3 years.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Most Eurasian sparrowhawks stay on the same territory for one breeding season, though others keep the same one for up to eight years.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A change of mate usually triggers the change in territory.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Older birds tend to stay in the same territory; failed breeding attempts make a move more likely.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The birds which kept the same territories had higher nest success, though it did not increase between years; females which moved experienced more success the year after changing territory.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The oldest known wild Eurasian sparrowhawk lived more than two decades; it was found dead in Denmark 20 years and 3 months after having been ringed.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Data analysis by the British Trust for Ornithology shows that the proportion of juveniles surviving their first year of life is 34%; adult survival from one year to the next is 69%.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Birds in their first year of life weigh less than adults, and are especially light in the first two months after reaching independence.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] There is probably high mortality, especially for young males, during this time.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A study in southern Scotland suggested that the greater mortality in young male birds may be due to their smaller size and the smaller size of their prey, which means that they can "last less long between meals".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Their size also means that their range of prey is restricted.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It has been estimated that a female Eurasian sparrowhawk of average weight could survive for seven days without feeding – three days longer than a male of average weight.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A study of female Eurasian sparrowhawks found "strong evidence" that their rate of survival increased for the first three years of life, and declined for the last five to six years.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Senescence (ageing) was the cause of the decline as the birds became older.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk population in Europe crashed in the second half of the 20th century.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The decline coincided with the introduction of cyclodiene insecticides – aldrin, dieldrin and heptachlor – used as seed dressings in agriculture in 1956.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Sub-lethal effects of these substances include irritability, convulsions and disorientation.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In west Germany, around 80% of nests before the 1950s produced young, but only 54% were successful in the 1960s and '70s.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In the United Kingdom, the species almost became extinct in East Anglia, where the chemicals were most widely used; in western and northern parts of the country, where the pesticides were not used, there were no declines.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Royal Society for the Protection of Birds bought its Coombes Valley nature reserve in Staffordshire because it was the only Eurasian sparrowhawk breeding site left in the English Midlands.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In the UK, the use of cyclodienes as seed dressings for autumn-sown cereals was banned in 1975 and the levels of the chemicals present in the bird population began to fall.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The population has largely recovered to pre-decline levels, with an increase seen in many areas, for example northern Europe.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In Sweden, the population also decreased drastically from the 1950s, but recovered again once organochlorines were banned in the 1970s.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In the UK, the failure rate at the egg stage had decreased from 17% to 6% by the year 2000, and the population had stabilised after reaching a peak in the 1990s.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Body tissue samples from Eurasian sparrowhawks are still analysed as part of the Predatory Bird Monitoring Scheme conducted by the UK government's Joint Nature Conservation Committee.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Although the average liver concentrations of polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) in Eurasian sparrowhawks were lower in birds that died in 2005 compared to those that died in 2004, there was not a significant or consistent decline in residues between 2000 and 2005.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The species suffered heavy persecution by 18th-century European landowners and gamekeepers, but withstood attempts to eradicate it.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] For example, on the estate at Sandringham in Norfolk, 1,645 'hawks' were killed between 1938 and 1950, with 1,115 taken between 1919 and 1926 at Langwell and Sandside in Caithness, Scotland.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The population was able to quickly replace lost birds – there is a high proportion of non-breeding, non-territorial birds able to fill vacant territories.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The habitat conserved with gamebirds in mind also suited this species and its prey; gamekeepers' more successful efforts to wipe out the Eurasian Goshawk and pine marten – predators of the Eurasian sparrowhawk – may have benefited it.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The population increased markedly when this pressure was relaxed, for example during the First and Second World Wars.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In the United Kingdom, research into the effect of predators on bird populations has been "a contentious issue", with "perceived conflict between the interests of nature conservationists and those involved in game shooting".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Declines in the populations of some British songbirds since the 1960s have coincided with considerable changes in agricultural practices and also large increases in the numbers of Eurasian sparrowhawks and European magpies.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] When the Eurasian sparrowhawk population declined because of organochlorine use, there was no great increase in the populations of songbirds.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In a 1949–1979 study of 13 passerine species breeding in a 40-acre (16-hectare) oakwood at Bookham Commons, Surrey, England, none was present in significantly greater numbers when Eurasian sparrowhawks were absent from the wood.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Many studies, mostly short-term, failed to find an effect on songbird populations caused by predatory birds such as Eurasian sparrowhawks.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] But analysis of long-term, large-scale national data from the UK's Common Bird Census demonstrated that the declines in farmland songbird populations since the 1960s are unlikely to have been caused by increased predation by Eurasian sparrowhawks and magpies.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The results of the study indicated that patterns of year-to-year songbird population change were the same at different sites, whether the predators were present or not.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Racing pigeon owners in Great Britain have said for many years that Eurasian sparrowhawks and peregrine falcons "cause serious and escalating losses" of pigeons and some have called for these birds of prey to be killed or removed from areas surrounding homing pigeon lofts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The study was carried out by the Central Science Laboratory; researchers worked with SHU members who provided data, information on pigeon rings found at peregrine falcon nests and pigeon carcasses.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] From January to April 2009, the Scottish Government conducted a trial translocation of Eurasian sparrowhawks from around racing pigeon lofts in Glasgow, Edinburgh, Kilmarnock, Stirling and Dumfries.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The trial, which cost £25,000, was supported by the Scottish Homing Union, representing the country's 3,500 pigeon fanciers.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The experiment was originally scheduled for early in 2008 but was postponed because it would have impinged on the birds' breeding season.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It was criticised by the government's own ecological adviser, Dr Ian Bainbridge, the government body Scottish Natural Heritage and organisations including the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds and the Scottish Society for Prevention of Cruelty to Animals.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The findings, released in January 2010, showed that only seven Eurasian sparrowhawks had been removed from the area from five pigeon lofts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] One hawk returned twice to the area of the loft, while new birds began to visit two other lofts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks are an effective urban adapter species in the UK and are thus non-threatened, however, recent search has suggested that they are prone to colliding with man-made structures such as buildings when hunting.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The Eurasian sparrowhawk has been used in falconry for centuries and was favoured by Emperor Akbar the Great (1542–1605) of the Mughal Empire.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] There is a tradition of using migrant Eurasian sparrowhawks to catch common quail in Tunisia and Georgia, where there are 500 registered *bazieri* (sparrowhawkers) and a monument to *bazieri* in the city of Poti.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Eurasian sparrowhawks are also popular in Ireland.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] At Cap Bon in Tunisia, and in Turkey, thousands are captured each year by falconers and used for hunting migrant common quails.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Although they were formerly released at the end of the season, many are now kept because of the scarcity of migrants.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In 17th century England, the Eurasian sparrowhawk was used by priests, reflecting their lowly status; whereas in the Middle Ages, they were favoured by ladies of noble and royal status because of their small size.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The falconer's name for a male Eurasian sparrowhawk is a "musket"; this is derived from the Latin word *musca*, meaning 'a fly', via the Old French word *moschet*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] "An austringer [falconer] undertaking to train a sparrowhawk should be in no doubt that he is taking on one of the most difficult hawks available." A female Eurasian sparrowhawk is considered a bad choice for a novice and the male is very difficult and demanding, even for an experienced handler.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] They have been described as "hysterical little hawks" but are also praised as courageous and providing "sport of the highest quality".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Philip Glasier describes Eurasian sparrowhawks as "in many ways superior to hunting with a larger short-wing [hawk]" and "extremely hard to tame".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] They are best suited for small quarry such as common starlings and common blackbirds but are also capable of taking common teal, Eurasian magpies, pheasants and partridges.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] A 19th century author remarked that this species was "the best of all hawks for landrails", now known as corn crakes.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In 1735, the *Sportsman's Dictionary* noted that "... she will serve in the winter as well as in the summer, and will fly at all kind of game more than the falcon.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In Slavic mythology, the sparrowhawk, known as *krahui* or *krahug*, is a sacred bird in Old Bohemian songs and lives in a grove of the gods.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] Holy sparrowhawks perch on the branches of an oak tree that grows from the grave of a murdered man, and "publish the foul deed".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The South Slavic name for this bird, *kobac* or *skobec*, comes from Proto-Slavic *kob* (doom), indicating that omens were read from its flight.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In some areas of England, it was believed that the common cuckoo turned into a Eurasian sparrowhawk in winter.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The surname *Spearhafoc*, later Sparhawk, Sparrowhawk was in use as a personal name in England before the Norman conquest of England in 1066.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The musket, or musquet, originally a kind of crossbow bolt, and later a small cannon, was named after the male Eurasian sparrowhawk because of its size.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The British Gloster Aircraft Company named one of their Mars series craft the Sparrowhawk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] In William Shakespeare's *The Merry Wives of Windsor*, Mrs Ford greets Robin, Falstaff's page, with the words "How now, my eyas musket", *eyas musket* meaning a lively young man (an eyas is a hawk nestling).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] The British Poet Laureate Ted Hughes wrote a poem entitled "A Sparrow-Hawk" which refers to this species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/accipiter-nisus] It also appears in Tennyson's *Idylls of the King*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The **large-billed reed warbler** (***Acrocephalus orinus***) is an Old World warbler in the genus *Acrocephalus*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The species has been dubbed as "the world's least known bird".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] It was known from a single specimen collected in India in 1867 and rediscovered in the wild in Thailand in 2006.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The identity of the bird caught in Thailand was established by matching DNA sequences extracted from feathers; the bird was released.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] After the rediscovery in the wild a second specimen was discovered amid *Acrocephalus dumetorum* specimens in the collections of the Natural History Museum at Tring.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] A breeding area was found in Afghanistan in 2009 and studies in 2011 pointed to its breeding in Kazakhstan and Tajikistan.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] One bird was found in the Baikka Wetland in Srimangal, Bangladesh on 7 December 2011.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] This species has the upper plumage and visible portions of wings and tail olive-brown while the underside is pale creamy with the underwing and axillaries paler.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The length is about 5 in (130 mm) with the tail being 2.3 in (58 mm) and the wing 2.4 in (61 mm) long.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The tarsus is 0.85 in (22 mm) while the bill from gape is 0.8 in (20 mm).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The first primary measures 0.35 in (8.9 mm) while the second is intermediate in length between the ninth and tenth.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The closed tail appears graduated with the difference between the longest and shortest feathers being 0.4 in (10 mm).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The type specimen was obtained in the Sutlej valley ("Sukedje valley") not far from Rampur.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The upper mandible is dark, but the cutting edges and entire lower mandible are pale.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The tarsi, toes and claws appear pale brown.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The hind claw is longer than in *A. dumetorum*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The tips of the tail feathers are pointed and more acutely lanceolate than in *A. dumetorum* or *A. concinens*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The primary tips are broad and rather squarer.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Recent observers note that it has a habit of fanning out its tail open as it forages.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The specimens from Afghanistan and Kazakhstan suggest that they breed in Central Asia and moult indicates that they migrate along the Himalayas to winter in northern India and Southeast Asia.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Sequence variation points to a stable or shrinking population structure.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] It was first collected by Allan Octavian Hume in the Sutlej Valley near Rampur, Himachal Pradesh, India on 13 November 1867.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] 1742) was first provisionally described as *Phyllopneuste macrorhyncha* (Hume, 1869) but the name was changed two years later to *Acrocephalus macrorhynchus* (Hume, 1871).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] H C Oberholser, however, pointed out in 1905 that this was unacceptable because a specimen from Egypt described by von Müller in 1853 as *Calamoherpe macrorhyncha* turned out to be *Acrocephalus stentoreus*; *Acrocephalus macrorhynchus* was abandoned in favour of *A. orinus*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The identity of the species was in question and until 2002 was considered as a synonym of the clamorous reed warbler (*A. stentoreus*).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Some others considered it an aberrant Blyth's reed warbler.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] A recent re-check of the morphology and the mtDNA suggested that it was a distinct species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] An additional ten new specimens in collections were identified in 2008.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] These included specimens collected by John Biddulph from Gilgit and W N Koelz from Zebak.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] On 27 March 2006 a living specimen was caught at the Laem Phak Bia Environmental Research and Development Project in Phetchaburi, Thailand by ornithologist Philip Round of Mahidol University.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The bird was ringed and two feathers were extracted; DNA from them was found to match the DNA of the 1867 specimen.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Based on the short and rounded wings, earlier studies had suggested that the species was likely to be a short-distant migrant or a resident.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] The rediscoveries of a second museum specimen from a different location and the wild specimen from Thailand suggest that this may not be so.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Some field identifications from West Bengal and central India were subsequently reported based on behaviour, but captured specimens did not appear to match the species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] A breeding site of the large-billed reed warbler, *Acrocephalus orinus*, was discovered in the Wakhan Corridor of the Pamir of north-eastern Afghanistan by researcher Robert Timmins of the Wildlife Conservation Society, who was studying avian communities in the Pamir Mountains.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] He came across a small brown warbler and recorded its song.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Timmins did not realize the importance of his discovery until he visited a Natural History Museum in Tring, England.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] There he examined a specimen of a large-billed reed warbler, which looked identical to the bird he had seen and recorded.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] A study by Russian ornithologists in 2011 indicated that the species had been misidentified as *A. dumetorum* in museum collections and that the species may be breeding in Tajikistan, Kyrgyzstan, eastern Uzbekistan and south-eastern Kazakhstan.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/acrocephalus-orinus] Nests were found in 2011 in the Panj river valley, Tajikistan.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] As the collector of Etawah, he saw the Indian Rebellion of 1857 as a result of misgovernance and made great efforts to improve the lives of the common people.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The district of Etawah was among the first to be returned to normality and over the next few years Hume's reforms led to the district being considered a model of development.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume rose in the ranks of the Indian Civil Service but like his father Joseph Hume, a Radical member of parliament, he was bold and outspoken in questioning British policies in India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He rose in 1871 to the position of secretary to the Department of Revenue, Agriculture, and Commerce under Lord Mayo who was assassinated a year later.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He did not get along as well with subsequent viceroys, and his criticism of Lord Lytton's policies led to his removal from the Secretariat in 1879.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He founded the journal *Stray Feathers* in which he and his subscribers recorded notes on birds from across India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He built up a vast collection of bird specimens at his home in Shimla by making collection expeditions and obtaining specimens through his network of correspondents.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Following the loss of manuscripts that he had long worked on in the hope of producing a magnum opus on the birds of India, he abandoned ornithology and gifted his collection to the Natural History Museum in London, where it continues to be the single largest collection of Indian bird skins.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He was briefly a follower of the theosophical movement founded by Madame Blavatsky.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He worked for Indian self-governance through the Indian National Congress that he founded.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He left India in 1894 to live in London from where he continued to take an interest in the Indian National Congress.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He maintained an interest in English botany and founded the South London Botanical Institute towards the end of his life.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was born in Westminster, London and baptised at St Mary's, Bryanston Square, a younger son (and the eighth of nine children) of Joseph Hume, the Radical Scottish member of parliament, by his marriage to Maria Burnley.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Until the age of eleven he was privately tutored growing up at the town house at 6 Bryanston Square in London and at their country estate, Burnley Hall in Norfolk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He was educated at University College Hospital, where he studied medicine and surgery and was then nominated to the Indian Civil Services which led him to study at the East India Company College, Haileybury.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Early influences included his friend John Stuart Mill and Herbert Spencer.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He briefly served as a junior midshipman aboard a navy vessel in the Mediterranean in 1842.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume sailed to India in 1849 and on reaching Calcutta, he stayed with his cousin James Hume, The following year, he joined the Bengal Civil Service at Etawah in the North-Western Provinces, in what is now Uttar Pradesh.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] His career in India included service as a district officer from 1849 to 1867, head of a central department from 1867 to 1870, and secretary to the Government from 1870 to 1879.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He married Mary Anne (26 May 1824, Meerut – 30 March 1890, Simla), daughter of Rivers Francis Grindall (1786–1832) in 1853.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He had a home, possibly used in summer, in Mussoorie in 1853.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1853 he clashed with his higher up, magistrate Mark B.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Thornhill of Dehra Dun, who had failed to cooperate on a case that Hume was dealing with in Mussoorie.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume in turn refused to hand over papers relating to civil cases that he was dealing with in Mussoorie.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume accused Thornhill of abuse of authority and Thornhill sent an armed contingent to forcibly take away the papers from Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The altercations resulted in his transfer to Aligarh.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] By May 1855 he was promoted to collector at Bulandshahr and then to officiating magistrate at Etawah in February 1856.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] It was only nine years after his entry to India that Hume faced the Indian Rebellion of 1857 during which time he was involved in several military actions for which he was created a Companion of the Bath in 1860.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Initially it appeared that he was safe in Etawah, not far from Meerut where the rebellion began but this changed and Hume had to take refuge in Agra fort for six months.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Nonetheless, all but one Indian official remained loyal and Hume resumed his position in Etawah in January 1858.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He built up an irregular force of 650 loyal Indian troops and took part in engagements with them.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume blamed British ineptitude for the uprising and pursued a policy of "mercy and forbearance" when dealing with the captured rebels.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Only seven persons were executed at the gallows on his orders.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The district of Etawah was restored to peace and order in a year, something that was not possible in most other parts.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Shortly after 1857, he set about in a range of reforms.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] As a District Officer in the Indian Civil Service, he began introducing free primary education and held public meetings for their support.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He made changes in the functioning of the police department and the separation of the judicial role.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Noting that there was very little reading material with educational content, he started, along with Koour Lutchman Singh, a Hindi language periodical, *Lokmitra* (*The People's Friend*) in 1859.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Originally meant only for Etawah, its fame spread.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume also organised and managed an Urdu journal *Muhib-i-riaya*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He took up the cause of education and founded scholarships for higher education.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1863 he moved for separate schools for juvenile delinquents rather than flogging and imprisonment which he saw as producing hardened criminals.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] His efforts led to a juvenile reformatory not far from Etawah.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He also started free schools in Etawah and by 1857 he established 181 schools with 5186 students including two girls.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The high school that he helped build with his own money is still in operation, now as a junior college, and it was said to have a floor plan resembling the letter "H".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] This, according to some was an indication of Hume's imperial ego.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume found the idea of earning revenue earned through liquor traffic repulsive and described it as "The wages of sin".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] With his progressive ideas on social reform, he advocated women's education, was against infanticide and enforced widowhood.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume laid out in Etawah, a neatly gridded commercial district that is now known as Humeganj but often pronounced *Homeganj*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1867 Hume became Commissioner of Customs for the North West Province, and in 1870 he became attached to the central government as Director-General of Agriculture.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1879 he returned to provincial government at Allahabad.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was very interested in the development of agriculture.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He believed that there was too much focus on obtaining revenue and no effort had been spent on improving the efficiency of agriculture.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He found an ally in Lord Mayo who supported the idea of developing a complete department of agriculture.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume noted in his *Agricultural reform in India* that Lord Mayo had been the only Viceroy who had any experience of working in the fields.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume made a number of suggestions for the improvement of agriculture placing carefully gathered evidence for his ideas.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He noted the poor yields of wheat, comparing them with estimates from the records of Emperor Akbar and yields of farms in Norfolk.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The department had charge on land revenue, settlements, advances for works in agricultural improvement, horticulture, livestock breeding, silk, fiber, forests, commerce and trade, salt, opium, excise, stamps, and industrial art.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] It also collected data and was in charge of censuses, the gazetteers, surveys, geology, and meteorology.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was made Secretary of this department in July 1871 leading to his move to Shimla.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] With the murder of Lord Mayo in the Andamans in 1872, Hume lost patronage and support for his work.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He however went about reforming the department of agriculture, streamlining the collection of meteorological data (the meteorological department was set up by order number 56 on 27 September 1875 signed by Hume) and statistics on cultivation and yield.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume proposed the idea of having experimental farms to demonstrate best practices to be set up in every district.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He proposed to develop fuelwood plantations "in every village in the drier portions of the country" and thereby provide a substitute heating and cooking fuel so that manure (dried cattle dung was used as fuel by the poor) could be returned to the land.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Such plantations, he wrote, were "*a thing that is entirely in accord with the traditions of the country – a thing that the people would understand, appreciate, and, with a little judicious pressure, cooperate in.*" He wanted model farms to be established in every district.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He noted that rural indebtedness was caused mainly by the use of land as security, a practice that had been introduced by the British.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume denounced it as another of "*the cruel blunders into which our narrow-minded, though wholly benevolent, desire to reproduce England in India has led us.*" Hume also wanted government-run banks, at least until cooperative banks could be established.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The department also supported the publication of several manuals on aspects of cultivation, a list of which Hume included as an appendix to his *Agricultural Reform in India*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume supported the introduction of cinchona and the project managed by George King to produce quinine in India and deliver malaria medication across India through the postal department at low cost.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was very outspoken and never feared to criticise when he thought the Government was in the wrong.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Even in 1861, he objected to the concentration of police and judicial functions in the hands of police superintendents.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In March 1861, he took a medical leave due to a breakdown from overwork and departed for Britain.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Before leaving, he condemned the flogging and punitive measures initiated by the provincial government as 'barbarous ... torture'.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He was allowed to return to Etawah only after apologising for the tone of his criticism.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He criticised the administration of Lord Lytton before 1879 which according to him, had cared little for the welfare and aspiration of the people of India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Lord Lytton's foreign policy according to Hume had led to the waste of "millions and millions of Indian money".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was critical of the land revenue policy and suggested that it was the cause of poverty in India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] His superiors were irritated and attempted to restrict his powers and this led him to publish a book on *Agricultural Reform in India* in 1879.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume noted that the free and honest expression was not only permitted but encouraged under Lord Mayo and that this freedom was curtailed under Lord Northbrook who succeeded Lord Mayo.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] When Lord Lytton succeeded Lord Northbrook, the situation worsened for Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1879 Hume went against the authorities.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The Government of Lord Lytton dismissed him from his position in the Secretariat.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] No clear reason was given except that it "*was based entirely on the consideration of what was most desirable in the interests of the public service*".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The press declared that his main wrongdoing was that he was too honest and too independent.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] It has been pointed out that he was victimised as he was out of step with the policies of the Government, often intruding into aspects of administration with critical opinions.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In spite of the humiliation of demotion, he did not resign immediately from service and it has been suggested that this was because he needed his salary to support the publication of *The Game Birds of India* that he was working on.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume retired from the civil service only in 1882.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1883 he wrote an open letter to the graduates of Calcutta University, having been a fellow of the University of Calcutta from 1870, calling upon them to form their own national political movement.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] This led in 1885 to the first session of the Indian National Congress held in Bombay.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1887, writing to the Public Commission of India, he made what was then a statement unexpected from a civil servant — *I look upon myself as a Native of India*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume's wife Mary died on 30 March 1890 and news of her death reached him just as he reached London on 1 April 1890.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Their only daughter Maria Jane Burnley ("Minnie") (3 January 1854 – 16 December 1927) married Ross Scott at Shimla on 28 December 1881.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Ross Scott had been the founding secretary of the Simla Eclectic Theosophical Society, whose founding president was Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Scott was for sometime Judicial Commissioner of Oudh before his death in 1908.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Maria moved to England where she became a member of another occult movement, the Hermetic Order of the Golden Dawn.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume's grandson Montague Allan Hume Scott served with the Royal Engineers in India, and received a Military Cross in 1917.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume left India in 1894 and settled at The Chalet, 4 Kingswood Road, Upper Norwood in south London.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He died at the age of eighty-three on 31 July 1912.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He was cremated and his ashes interred in Brookwood Cemetery.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The bazaar in Etawah was closed on hearing of his death and the Collector, H.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Nevill, presided over a memorial meeting.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The Indian postal department issued a commemorative stamp with his portrait in 1973 and a special cover depicting Rothney Castle, his home in Shimla, was released in 2013.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was noted for his pro-Indian activities.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He believed that the British regime had failed in India, not from any lack of good attention but rather because of insufficient knowledge.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] There were agrarian riots in the Deccan and Bombay, and Hume, according to some early writers like Pattabhi Sitaramayya, suggested that an Indian Union would be a good safety valve and outlet to avoid further unrest.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] This so-called "safety valve" theory of the origin of the Congress, first introduced by W.C.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Bonnerjee, has been refuted on the basis that the seven volumes of the secret report were fictional.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] They were created by William Wedderburn to portray Hume as a British patriot.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1886 he published a pamphlet *The Old Man's Hope* in which he examined poverty in India, questioning charity as a solution for the problem.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Here he makes a case for Richard Cobden's Anti-Corn Law League as a model for the struggle in India through the formation of a representative body.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The idea of the Indian National Union took shape and Hume initially had some support from Lord Dufferin for this, although the latter wished to have no official link to it.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Dufferin's support was short-lived and in some of his letters he went so far as to call Hume an "idiot", "arch-impostor", and "mischievous busy-body." Dufferin's successor Lansdowne refused to have any dialogue with Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Other supporters in England included James Caird (who had also clashed with Lytton over the management of famine in India) and John Bright.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume also founded an Indian Telegraph Union to fund the transfer of news of Indian matters to newspapers in England and Scotland without interference from British Indian officials who controlled telegrams sent by Reuters.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] It has been suggested that the idea of the congress was originally conceived in a private meeting of seventeen men after a Theosophical Convention held at Madras in December 1884 but no evidence exists.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume took the initiative, and it was in March 1885, when a notice was first issued to convene the first Indian National Union to meet at Poona the following December.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] He attempted to increase the Congress base by bringing in more farmers, townspeople and Muslims between 1886 and 1887 and this created a backlash from the British, leading to backtracking by the Congress.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hume was disappointed when Congress opposed moves to raise the age of marriage for Indian girls and failed to focus on issues of poverty.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Some Indian princes did not like the idea of democracy and some organisations like the United Indian Patriotic Association went about trying to undermine the Congress by showing it as an organisation with a seditious character.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] There was also major rifts along religious lines within the Congress on issues such as the Age of Consent Bill.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] In 1892, he tried to get the members to act, warning of a violent agrarian revolution but this only outraged the British establishment and frightened the Congress leaders.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Disappointed by the continued lack of Indian leaders willing to work for the cause of national emancipation, Hume left India in 1894.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Many Anglo-Indians were against the idea of the Indian National Congress.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] The press in India tended to look upon it negatively, so much so that Hume is said to have held a very low opinion of journalists even later in life.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] A satirical work on native rule, *India in 1983*, published (anonymously but thought to be written by T.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p01] Hart Davies) in 1888 included a character derisively called "A.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] From early days, Hume had a special interest in science.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] During his career in Etawah, he built up a personal collection of bird specimens, however the first collection that he made was destroyed during the 1857 rebellion.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] After 1857 Hume made several expeditions to collect birds both on health leave and where work took him.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He was Collector and Magistrate of Etawah from 1856 to 1867 during which time he studied the birds of that area.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Around 1867 he transferred about 2500 specimens from his collection to a museum in Agra.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] His most systematic work however began after he moved to Shimla.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He later became Commissioner of Inland Customs which made him responsible for the control of 2,500 miles (4,000 km) of coast from near Peshawar in the northwest to Cuttack on the Bay of Bengal.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He travelled on horseback and camel in areas of Rajasthan to negotiate treaties with various local maharajas to control the export of salt, and during these travels he took note of the birdlife.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume appears to have planned a comprehensive work on the birds of India around 1870 and a "forthcoming comprehensive work" finds mention in the second edition of *The Cyclopaedia of India* (1871) by his cousin Edward Balfour.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] His systematic plan to survey and document the birds of the Indian Subcontinent began in earnest after he started accumulating the largest collection of Asiatic birds in his personal museum and library at home in Rothney Castle on Jakko Hill, Simla.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Rothney Castle, originally Rothney House was built by Colonel Octavius Edward Rothney (1824–1881) and later owned by P.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Mitchell, C.I.E. from whom Hume bought it and converted it into a palatial house with the hope that it might be bought by the Government as a Viceregal residence since the Governor-General then occupied *Peterhoff*, a building too small for large parties.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume spent over two hundred thousand pounds on the grounds and buildings.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He added enormous reception rooms suitable for large dinner parties and balls, as well as a magnificent conservatory and spacious hall with walls displaying his superb collection of Indian horns.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He used a large room for his bird museum.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He hired a European gardener, and made the grounds and conservatory a perpetual horticultural exhibition, to which he courteously admitted all visitors.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Rothney Castle could only be reached by a steep road, and was never purchased by the British Government.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume made several expeditions almost solely to study ornithology, the largest being an expedition to the Indus area begun in late November 1871 and continued until the end of February 1872.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In March 1873, he visited the Andaman and Nicobar Islands in the Bay of Bengal along with geologists Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Ferdinand Stoliczka and Valentine Ball of the Geological Survey of India and James Wood-Mason of the Indian Museum in Calcutta.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] They were also accompanied by Surgeon-Major Joseph Dougall, medical superintendent at Port Blair, six native trappers-skinners, and supported by others like Jeremiah Nelson Homfray, superintendent of the Andaman orphanage.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In 1875, he made an expedition to the Laccadive Islands aboard the marine survey vessel IGS *Clyde* under the command of Staff-Commander Ellis and accompanied by surgeon-naturalist James Armstrong of the Marine Survey.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The official purpose of the visit was ostensibly to examine proposed sites for lighthouses.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] During this expedition Hume collected many bird specimens, apart from conducting a bathymetric survey to determine whether the island chain was separated from continental India by a deep canyon.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] And in 1881 he made his last ornithological expedition to Manipur, a visit in which he collected and described the Manipur bush quail (*Perdicula manipurensis*), a bird that has remained obscure with few reliable reports since.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume spent an extra day with his assistants cutting down a large tract of grass so that he could obtain specimens of this species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This expedition was made on special leave following his demotion from the Central Government to a junior position on the Board of Revenue of the North Western Provinces.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Apart from personal travel, he also sent out a trained bird-skinner to accompany officers travelling in areas of ornithological interest such as Afghanistan.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Around 1878 he was spending about £1500 a year on his ornithological surveys.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume was a member of the Asiatic Society of Bengal from January 1870 to 1891 and admitted Fellow of the Linnean Society on 3 November 1904.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] After returning to England in 1890 he also became president of the Dulwich Liberal and Radical Association.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume used his vast bird collection to good use as editor of his journal *Stray Feathers*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He also intended to produce a comprehensive publication on the birds of India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume employed William Ruxton Davison, who was brought to notice by Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] George King, as a curator for his personal bird collection.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume trained Davison and sent him out annually on collection trips to various parts of India as he himself was held up with official responsibilities.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In 1883 Hume returned from a trip to find that many pages of the manuscripts that he had maintained over the years had been stolen and sold off as waste paper by a servant.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume was completely devastated and he began to lose interest in ornithology due to this theft and a landslip, caused by heavy rains in Simla, which had damaged his museum and many of the specimens.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He wrote to the British Museum wishing to donate his collection on certain conditions.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] One of the conditions was that the collection was to be examined by Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Bowdler Sharpe and personally packed by him, apart from raising Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Sharpe's rank and salary due to the additional burden on his work caused by his collection.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The British Museum was unable to heed his many conditions.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] It was only in 1885, after the destruction of nearly 20,000 specimens, that alarm bells were raised by Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Sharpe and the museum authorities let him visit India to supervise the transfer of the specimens to the British Museum.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The Hume collection of birds was packed into 47 cases made of deodar wood constructed on site without nails that could potentially damage specimens and each case weighing about half a ton was transported down the hill to a bullock cart to Kalka and finally the port in Bombay.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The material that went to the British Museum in 1885 consisted of 82,000 specimens of which 75,577 (258 being type specimens) were finally placed in the museum.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] A breakup of that collection is as follows (old names retained).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume had destroyed 20,000 specimens prior to this as they had been damaged by dermestid beetles.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In addition his donations included 223 game trophies and 371 mammal skins.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The Hume Collection contained 258 type specimens.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In addition there were nearly 400 mammal specimens including new species such as *Hadromys humei*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The egg collection was made up of carefully authenticated contributions from knowledgeable contacts and on the authenticity and importance of the collection, E.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Oates noted in the 1901 *Catalogue of the Collection of Birds' Eggs in the British Museum* (Volume 1) that the collection was made up of specimens of known provenance and not accumulated through indiscriminate purchases as tended to be the case with many other collectors.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume and his collector Davison took an interest in plants as well.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Specimens were collected even on the first expedition to the Lakshadweep in 1875 were studied by George King and later by David Prain.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's herbarium specimens were donated to the collection of the Botanical Survey of India at Calcutta.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume described many species, some of which are now considered as subspecies.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] A single genus name that he erected survives in use while others such as *Heteroglaux* Hume, 1873 have sunk into synonymy since.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In addition to birds, he described a species of goat as *Ovis blanfordi* in 1877 based on a variation in the horns.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] It is now considered a variant of the urial (*Ovis vignei*).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In his concept of species, Hume was an essentialist and held the idea that small but constant differences defined species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He appreciated the ideas of speciation and how it contradicted divine creation but preferred to maintain a position that did not reject a Creator.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The use of trinomials had not yet gone into regular usage during Hume's time.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The following subspecies are current placements of taxa that were named as new species by Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] An additional species, the large-billed reed-warbler *Acrocephalus orinus* was known from just one specimen collected by him in 1869 but the name that he used, *magnirostris*, was found to be preoccupied and replaced by the name *orinus* provided by Harry Oberholser in 1905.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The status of the species was contested until DNA comparisons with similar species in 2002 suggested that it was a valid species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] It was only in 2006 that the species was seen in the wild in Thailand, with a match to the specimens confirmed using DNA sequencing.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Later searches in museums led to several other specimens that had been overlooked and based on the specimen localities, a breeding region was located in Tajikistan and documented in 2011.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This was Hume's first major work on birds.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] It had 422 pages and accounts of 81 species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] It was dedicated to Edward Blyth and Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Jerdon who, he wrote "[had] done more for Indian Ornithology than all other modern observers put together" and he described himself as "their friend and pupil".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He hoped that his collation, which he noted as being of a poor quality, would form a "nucleus round which future observation may crystallise" and that others around the country could help him "fill in many of the woeful blanks remaining in record".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He offered to supply anyone interested with a list of species for which more information was needed and noted that Ceylon and Burma were major geographical gaps as he had no correspondents from there.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume was a careful reader of the ornithological literature and routinely communicated on them.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In 1875 he noted that Friedrich Wilhelm Meves had confirmed through chemical analysis that the brown coloration of lammergeiers was due to an external deposition of iron-oxide.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume wrote in the Scrap Book and commented on Meves' theory that the source may have been blood rather than through bathing in iron-rich water.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume had repeated the chemical analysis and confirmed the presence of iron.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume started the quarterly journal *Stray Feathers* in 1872.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] At that time the only journal for the Indian region that published on ornithology was the *Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal* and Hume published only two letters in 1870, mainly being a list of errors in the list of Godwin-Austen which had been reduced to an abstract.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Several other papers that he submitted to the *Ibis* had not been published and delays in post were common.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The President of the Asiatic Society of Bengal, Thomas Oldham, in the annual address for 1873 wrote – "We could have wished that the author had completed the several works which he had already commenced, rather than started a new publication.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He wrote extensively on his own observation as well as critical reviews of all the ornithological works of the time and earned himself the nickname of *Pope of Indian ornithology*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He critiqued a monograph on parrots, *Die Papageien* by Friedrich Hermann Otto Finsch suggesting that name changes (by "cabinet naturalists") were aimed at claiming authority to species without the trouble of actually discovering them.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume in turn was attacked, for instance by Viscount Walden, but Finsch became a friend and Hume named a species, *Psittacula finschii*, after him.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In his younger days Hume had studied some geology from the likes of Gideon Mantell and appreciated the synthesis of ideas from other fields into ornithology.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume included in 1872, a detailed article on the osteology of birds in relation to their classification written by Richard Lydekker who was then in the Geological Survey of India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The early meteorological work in India was done within the department headed by Hume and he saw the value of meteorology in the study of bird distributions.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In a work comparing the rainfall zones, he notes how the high rainfall zones indicated affinities to the Malayan fauna.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume sometimes mixed personal beliefs in notes that he published in *Stray Feathers*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] For instance he believed that vultures soared by altering the physics ("altered polarity") of their body and repelling the force of gravity.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He further noted that this ability was normal in birds and could be acquired by humans by maintaining spiritual purity, claiming that he knew of at least three Indian Yogis and numerous saints in the past with this ability of *"aethrobacy*".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume corresponded with a large number of ornithologists and sportsmen who helped him by reporting from various parts of India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] More than 200 correspondents are listed in his *Game Birds* alone and they probably represent only a fraction of the subscribers of *Stray Feathers*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This large network made it possible for Hume to cover a much larger geographic region in his ornithological work.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] During the lifetime of Hume, Blyth was considered the father of Indian ornithology.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's achievement which made use of a large network of correspondents was recognised even during his time.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] James Murray noted of Hume that "the palm is his as an authority above the rest" when it came to the birds of India and that all future work would be built upon his work.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Many of Hume's correspondents ("coadjutors" as he referred to them) were eminent naturalists and sportsmen who were posted in India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume exchanged skins with other collectors.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] A collection made principally by Hume that belonged to the Earl of Northbrook was gifted to Oxford University in 1877.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] One of his correspondents, Louis Mandelli from Darjeeling, stands out by claiming that he was swindled in these skin exchanges.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He claimed that Hume took skins of rarer species in exchange for the skins of common birds but the credibility of the complaint has been doubted.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume named *Arborophila mandelli* after Mandelli in 1874.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The only other naturalist to question Hume's veracity was A.L.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Butler who met a Nicobar islander whom Hume had described as diving nearly stark naked and capturing fish with his bare hands.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Butler found the man in denial of such fishing techniques.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume corresponded and stayed up to date with the works of ornithologists outside India including R.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Bowdler Sharpe, the Marquis of Tweeddale, Père David, Henry Eeles Dresser, Benedykt Dybowski, John Henry Gurney, J.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Gurney, Jr., Johann Friedrich Naumann, Nikolai Severtzov and Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He helped George Ernest Shelley with specimens from India aiding the publication of a monograph on the sunbirds of the world (1876–1880).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's vast collection from across India was possible because he began to correspond with coadjutors across India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He ensured that these contributors made accurate notes, and obtained and processed specimens carefully.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The *Vade Mecum* was published to save him the trouble of sending notes to potential collaborators who sought advice.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Materials for preservation are carefully tailored for India with the provision of the local names for ingredients and methods to prepare glues and preservatives with easy to find equipment.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Apart from skinning and preservation, the book also covers matters of observation, keeping records, the use of natives to capture birds, obtain eggs and the care needed in obtaining other information apart from care in labelling.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The three volume work on the game birds was made using contributions and notes from a network of 200 or more correspondents.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume delegated the task of getting the plates made to Marshall.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The chromolithographs of the birds were drawn by W.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Herbert, Stanley Wilson and others and the plates were produced by F.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume had sent specific notes on colours of soft parts and instructions to the artists.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He was dissatisfied with many of the plates and included additional notes on the plates in the book.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This book was started at the point when the government demoted Hume and only the need to finance the publication of this book prevented him from retiring from service.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He had estimated that it would cost £4000 to publish it and he retired from service on 1 January 1882 after the publication.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This was another major work by Hume and in it he covered descriptions of the nests, eggs and the breeding seasons of most Indian bird species.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] It makes use of notes from contributors to his journals as well as other correspondents and works of the time.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] A second edition of this book was made in 1889 which was edited by Eugene William Oates.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This was published when he had himself given up all interest in ornithology, an event precipitated by the loss of his manuscripts through the actions of a servant.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] This nearly marked the end of Hume's interest in ornithology.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's last piece of ornithological writing was part of an *Introduction to the Scientific Results of the Second Yarkand Mission* in 1891, an official publication on the contributions of Dr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Ferdinand Stoliczka, who died during the return journey on this mission.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Stoliczka in a dying request had asked that Hume edit the volume on ornithology.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's interest in theosophy took root around 1879.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] An 1880 newspaper reports the initiation of his daughter and wife into the movement.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume did not have great regard for institutional Christianity, but believed in the immortality of the soul and in the idea of a supreme ultimate.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume wanted to become a *chela* (student) of the Tibetan spiritual gurus.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] During the few years of his connection with the Theosophical Society Hume wrote three articles on *Fragments of Occult Truth* under the pseudonym "H.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] These were written in response to questions from Mr.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He also privately printed several Theosophical pamphlets titled *Hints on Esoteric Theosophy*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The later numbers of the Fragments, in answer to the same enquirer, were written by A.P.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Sinnett and signed by him, as authorised by Mahatma K.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] H., *A Lay-Chela.* Hume also wrote under the pseudonym "Aletheia".
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Madame Blavatsky was a regular visitor at Hume's Rothney castle at Simla and an account of her visit may be found in *Simla, Past and Present* by Edward John Buck (whose father Sir Edward Charles Buck succeeded Hume as secretary to the Revenue and Agricultural Department).
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] A long story about Hume and his wife appears in A.P.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Sinnett's book *The Occult World*, and the synopsis was published in a local paper of India.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The story relates how at a dinner party, Madame Blavatsky asked Mrs Hume if there was anything she wanted.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] She replied that there was a brooch, her mother had given her, that had gone out of her possession some time ago.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Blavatsky said she would try to recover it through occult means.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] After some interlude, later that evening, the brooch was found in a garden, where the party was directed by Blavatsky.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] According to John Murdoch (1894), the brooch had been given by Mrs.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume to her daughter who had given it to a man she admired.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Blavatsky had happened to meet the man in Bombay and obtained the brooch in return for money.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Blavatsky allegedly planted it in the garden before directing people to the location through what she claimed as occult techniques.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] After the incident, Hume too had privately expressed grave doubts on the powers attributed to Madame Blavatsky.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] He subsequently held a meeting with some of the Indian members of the Theosophical Society and suggested that they join hands with him to force the resignation of Blavatsky and sixteen other members for their role as accomplices in fraud.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Those present could however not agree to the idea of seeking the resignation of their founder.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume also tried to write a book on the philosophical basis of Theosophy.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] His drafts were strongly disapproved by many of the key Theosophists.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume soon fell out of favour with the Theosophists and lost all interest in the theosophical movement in 1883.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's interest in theosophy brought him into contact with many independent Indian thinkers like Gopal Krishna Gokhale who also had nationalist ideas and this led to the idea of creating the Indian National Congress.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume's immersion into the theosophical movement led him to become a vegetarian and also to give up killing birds for their specimens.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] After the loss of his manuscript containing his lifetime of ornithological notes, Hume gave up ornithology and took great interest in horticulture around his home in Shimla.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume took an interest in wild plants and especially on invasive species although his botanical publishing was sparse with only three short notes between 1901 and 1902 including one on a variety of *Scirpus maritimus*, and another on the flowering of *Impatiens roylei*.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Griffin in 1901 to help develop a herbarium of botanical specimens.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume would arrange his plants on herbarium sheets in artistic positions before pressing them.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The two made many botanical trips including one to Down in Kent to seek some of the rare orchids that had been collected by Darwin.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In 1910, Hume bought the premises of 323 Norwood Road, and modified it to have a herbarium and library.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] One of the aims of the institute was to help promote botany as a means for mental culture and relaxation, an idea that was not shared by Henry Groves, a trustee for the institute.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume objected to advertisement and refused to have any public ceremony to open the institute.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Griffin and Hume endowed the institute with £10,000.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Frederick Townsend, F.L.S., an eminent botanist, who died in 1905, had left instructions that his herbarium and collection was to be given to the institute, which was then only being contemplated.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Hume left £15,000 in his will for the maintenance of the botanical institute.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] In the years leading up to the establishment of the institute, Hume built up links with many of the leading botanists of his day.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] Davey and in the *Flora of Cornwall* (1909), Davey thanks Hume as his companion on excursions in Cornwall and Devon, and for help in the compilation of the 'Flora', publication of which was financed by Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The SLBI has since grown to hold a herbarium of approximately 100,000 specimens mostly of flowering plants from Europe including many collected by Hume.
[src:allan-octavian-hume/allan-octavian-hume-p02] The collection was later augmented by the addition of other herbaria over the years, and has significant collections of *Rubus* (bramble) species and of the Shetland flora.
